ce:section.ce:para:
Photo-induced cancer therapy primarily relies on the principles of PDT and PTT, each harnessing distinct mechanisms to induce localized cell death in targeted tumor tissues. In PDT, a PS is employed to generate ROS upon exposure to light of a specific wavelength, inducing localized cell death [130]. On the other hand, PTT employs PA that can absorb light to convert light energy into heat, thereby elevating the temperature of targeted tumor tissues and resulting in localized cell death [5]. For an optimal and synergistic approach in photo-induced cancer therapy, the concurrent utilization of PS and PA is paramount. These components possess a dual capacity, proficiently transforming light energy into both ROS generation and local hyperthermia [131]. This intricate interplay enabled the realization of both PDT and PTT effects, culminating in a comprehensive and potent treatment strategy [131]. The underlying mechanism of PDT and PTT are delineated through the behaviour of PS or PA upon exposure to light of a specific wavelength (Fig. 2
                     ). Upon absorption of light energy, electrons are excited from the S0 to the excited singlet state (S1). The subsequent de-excitation of these excited states transpires through three distinct pathways: (1) non-radiative relaxation, where electrons revert from S1 to S0, releasing energy in the form of heat; (2) radiative relaxation, where electrons return from S1 to S0, emitting fluorescence luminescence (FL); and (3) intersystem crossing, facilitating the transition from S1 to the excited triplet state (T1) [15]. Following this, the T1 state can undergo different inactivation routes. These encompass non-radiative relaxation with heat release, radiative relaxation emitting phosphoresce luminescence (PL), the generation of free radicals inducing ROS production such as H2O2, superoxide anion (O2
                     –), and hydroxyl radicals (•OH) via interactions with oxygen (O2) or water (H2O) (Type I electron transfer, PDT); and energy transfer, sensitizing O2 or H2O to produce singlet oxygen (1O2) (Type II energy transfer, PDT) [15,132]. The excitation of PS can result in different pathways of excited state inactivation, offering diverse applications in biomedical fields including bioimaging, acoustic imaging, and cancer therapy [5,15]. The amalgamation of PDT and PTT offers opportunities for synergistic cancer treatment and imaging guidance. The ROS generated during PDT exerts an augmentative effect on PTT by inhibiting heat shock proteins [15]. In parallel, the heat induced by PTT enhances PDT efficacy by elevating the oxygen content within tumor cells [15]. This intricate interplay not only underscores the interconnectedness of these approaches but also underscores their potential for revolutionizing cancer treatment strategies, offering heightened precision, efficacy, and therapeutic outcomes.

Many CDs exhibit fluorescence across a spectrum ranging from blue to NIR, providing a valuable tool for imaging-guided therapy. In the context of PDT, CDs act as PS that can absorb light and transfer the absorbed energy to surrounding molecules, leading to the generation of ROS [15]. CDs possess unique optical properties that allowed them to efficiently absorb light, especially in the UV and NIR regions of the electromagnetic spectrum [140]. Upon light absorption, the electrons in the CDs’ molecular structure get excited to higher energy levels [141]. The energy absorbed by the CDs is then transferred to nearby molecular O2, leading to its conversion from the ground triplet state (3O2) to the highly reactive 1O2 
                        [142]. This 1O2 species is a powerful oxidizing agent and is known to cause oxidative stress and damage within cells. The generated ROS are short-lived and highly reactive [143]. When they come into contact with cellular components such as lipids, proteins, and DNA, they will initiate a series of oxidative reactions [143]. This light-triggered generation of ROS will induce localized oxidative stress, leading to apoptosis or necrosis of targeted cells. Particularly, the elevated ROS level triggers a cascade of cellular reactions including the activation of the MAPK signalling pathway which plays a crucial role in modulating fundamental cellular processes such as growth, differentiation, migration, proliferation and apoptosis in response to environmental stimuli [144]. This further induced the release of proapoptotic proteins such as cytochrome c and apoptosis protease activator-1 (Apaf-1) to form apoptotic bodies which in turn trigger the activation of caspase-9 followed by caspase-3, 6 and 7 (Fig. 3
                        ) [145,146]. This ultimately leads to cellular damage, disruption of vital cellular fractions, damage the DNA fragment and triggers apoptotic pathways, resulting in the demise of cancer cells [15,147].
